# API Design Standards

## Versioning — every public API is versioned from day one

```text
# HTTP: version in URL path, never in headers or query params
/v1/agents
/v1/agents/{id}/memories
/v1/tokens

# gRPC: version in package name
package ibex.auth.v1;
```

## Error envelope — all error responses use the stable envelope

```json
{
  "error": {
    "code": "RATE_LIMITED",
    "message": "Rate limit exceeded. Retry after the indicated interval.",
    "request_id": "01HXYZ..."
  }
}
```

- `code`: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE from `packages/apierror` canonical registry. Never a raw string literal.
- `message`: Human-readable. Safe to show to the end user. No internal details.
- `request_id`: Always populated. Used for correlating with logs.

**Do not** add `details`, `stack_trace`, `cause`, or any internal information to the error body. Those go in logs, not responses.

## Status codes — use the correct one, every time

| Situation | Code |
|---|---|
| Validation failure (bad field value) | 400 |
| Missing required field | 400 |
| Missing or invalid auth token | 401 |
| Valid token, insufficient permissions | 403 |
| Cross-org resource access | 403 (not 404) |
| Resource not found (own org) | 404 |
| Method not allowed | 405 |
| Rate limited | 429 |
| Dependency (auth/DB) unavailable | 503 |
| Request timed out | 504 |

## Pagination — all list endpoints are paginated from day one

```json
// Request: GET /v1/agents?limit=20&cursor=eyJ...
// Response:
{
  "agents": [...],
  "next_cursor": "eyJ...",  // null if no more pages
  "total": null             // do NOT return total count (expensive at scale)
}
```

Use cursor-based pagination (not page number). Cursor encodes the last seen `(created_at, id)` tuple, base64-encoded. Page number pagination is an anti-pattern at scale (deep pages are expensive; inconsistent under inserts).

## Idempotency — mutations accept idempotency keys

```text
POST /v1/tokens
Idempotency-Key: client-generated-uuid
```

If the same `Idempotency-Key` is seen within 24 hours, return the original response. This allows clients to safely retry POST/PUT/DELETE without creating duplicates.

## Response shapes — consistent across the entire API

```go
// Every response (success or error) has Content-Type: application/json
// Every success response for a resource returns the full resource object
// Never return 200 with an empty body (use 204 No Content)
// Never return different shapes for the same endpoint depending on parameters
```

## Naming conventions for REST endpoints

```text
Collection:     GET    /v1/agents           → list
Single:         GET    /v1/agents/{id}      → get
Create:         POST   /v1/agents           → create
Update (full):  PUT    /v1/agents/{id}      → replace
Update (patch): PATCH  /v1/agents/{id}      → partial update
Delete:         DELETE /v1/agents/{id}      → soft delete

Sub-resources:  GET    /v1/agents/{id}/memories
Actions:        POST   /v1/agents/{id}/activate    ← verb-based action
                POST   /v1/tokens/{id}/revoke
```
